441 10.8122 19.9254 10.8098 19.9058V10.6071C10.8107 9.18295 11.2173 7.78848 11.9819 6.58696C12.7466 5.38544 13.8377 4.42659 15.1275 3.82264C16.4173 3.21869 17.8524 2.99464 19.2649 3.1767C20.6775 3.35876 22.0089 3.93941 23.1034 4.85067C23.0427 4.88379 22.937 4.94215 22.8668 4.98473L14.9024 9.58517C14.7025 9.69878 14.5366 9.86356 14.4215 10.0626C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>Voin asserts that the progression of both science and the evolution of living beings, particularly higher animals, has been directed towards the enhancement of information transmission from one generation to the next. In the human context, tribes that could more efficiently pass on knowledge to younger generations have been more successful in the struggle for survival. This quality of information transfer is directly tied to the strictness and unambiguity of the concepts used. The less strict the concepts, the more likely they are to be misinterpreted or misunderstood.</p><p>Science, too, has evolved towards stricter concepts. Voin raises the question of whether science has already achieved absolute strictness and unambiguity in its concepts. He suggests that rational science has been able to achieve absolute clarity in its concepts, citing Euclid's geometry as an example where the concepts of a line and a point are uniquely defined using a system of five axioms. In physics, an ideal fluid, defined by zero compressibility and viscosity, is another instance of an absolutely unambiguous definition.</p><p>However, the achievement of unambiguous definitions in science has led to another challenge—linking these concepts to real-world objects. In reality, no objects perfectly correspond to these strict, unambiguous definitions. There are no perfectly straight lines or ideal fluids. Every line, even a beam of light, has a non-zero curvature at any point, and all fluids, to some extent, are compressible and have non-zero viscosity.</p><p>While for any non-empty concept with an unambiguous definition, there are objects that are so close to the absolute values in the definition that the differences are negligible, there are also objects where the deviation from the nominal definition cannot be overlooked.</p><p>Voin concludes that although science begins with common sense, it cannot end with it. Relying on common sense to determine the applicability of a theory is insufficient—hence the necessity for scientific theory.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="flex ml-auto gap-2 rounded-md p-1 hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2"></path><rect x="8" y="2" width="8" height="4" rx="1" ry="1"></rect></svg></button><div class="flex gap-1"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M14 9V5a3 3 0 0 0-3-3l-4 9v11h11.28a2 2 0 0 0 2-1.7l1.38-9a2 2 0 0 0-2-2.3zM7 22H4a2 2 0 0 1-2-2v-7a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h3"></path></svg></button><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M10 15v4a3 3 0 0 0 3 3l4-9V2H5.72a2 2 0 0 0-2 1.7l-1.38 9a2 2 0 0 0 2 2.3zm7-13h2.67A2.31 2.31 0 0 1 22 4v7a2.31 2.31 0 0 1-2.33 2H17"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 dark:bg-gray-800"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col relative items-end"><div class="w-[30px]"><div class="relative flex"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; max-width: 100%;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; max-width: 100%;"><img alt="" aria-hidden="true" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20version=%271.1%27%20width=%2738%27%20height=%2738%27/%3e" style="display: block; max-width: 100%; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;"></span><img alt="User" src="https://chat.openai.com/_next/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2Fa%2FAGNmyxbfUJGaUXxADgtF19b5ZhmrVKp8-tY9hQf2Jfmp%3Ds96-c&amp;w=96&amp;q=75" decoding="async" data-nimg="intrinsic" class="rounded-sm" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" width="30" height="30"></span></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">According to the unified method of justification, this problem is
solved as follows. An unambiguous definition of the concept is
introduced in the form that I call the nominal definition. Namely, the
properties of real objects that fall under the definition are listed, and a
quantitative measure of the presence of this property in the object is
indicated (O compressibility and 0 viscosity for an ideal fluid). And then
the allowed deviations for the indicated properties from the nominal
value of the definition are indicated and thus the set of real objects
that satisfy this definition is uniquely determined. And the allowed
deviations are determined by the accuracy and reliability of the
predictions of our theory, which are required or satisfy us when solving
a specific problem
Anticipating possible questions in this place, I will explain. Yes, in
real science we do not always observe even the formulation of
definitions of concepts in the style of the niminal definition, not to
mention the indication of permissible deviations from the nominal
definition. But, either they are implied, although they are not clearly
formulated, or it is not science on this basis. What does "implied"
mean? Well let's say, in geometric optics, light rays are considered
straight, and straightness is understood in accordance with the strict
unambiguous definition of a straight line, whether it is Euclidean or
through zero curvature, etc., although this is not specifically stipulated
because it is clear anyway. And the permissible deviations of the rays
from zero curvature are not indicated, since under terrestrial
conditions they are so small that we will certainly be within the
tolerance, whatever it may be according to the requirements of the
problem being solved. But if we begin to apply geometric optics in
space, then, given that the rays of light are bentin the vicinity of stars
under the influence of their gravity, we must set these allowable
deviations. Otherwise it is not science, otherwise we cannot guarantee
the accuracy and reliability of our predictions
There is also a question in this paragraph concerning the
humanities, for the vast majority of concepts in which there is no
quantitative measure of their attributes and, therefore, neither the face
value nor the allowable deviation on this basis can be set. There are no
kilograms or meters, neither justice, nor love, etc. It follows from this
that the unified method of justification cannot be applied absolutely
strictly here. But in reality nothing is absolute. Absoluteness is
achievable only in the realm of abstractions. And in the field of natural
sciences we can absolutely strictly set the definition of concepts, but
the binding of concepts to a specific set of objects of reality cannot be
absolutely accurate there either, because it is limited by the accuracy
of our measurements. Thus, a unified method of substantiation is the
same idealization of the real practice of rational science as its own
concepts of the type of an ideal fluid are idealization of real objects
Those it serves as the ideal that science should achieve to the extent
that it can do it or that practically suits us. In the natural sciences, as a
rule, greater accuracy is required and achievable in linking concepts to
a multitude of objects of reality, well, and where it is not achievable, we
are forced to admit that science !s still powerless here. In In the
humanities, on the one hand, we do not need such high precision as in
the natural sciences. On the other hand, it would be a mistake to think
that no accuracy in defining concepts and linking them to reality is
achievable here. In the humanities, as a rule, there is no quantitative
measure for the properties listed in the definition of a concept. But this
does not mean that there is no commensurability itself. We cannot
quantify the talent of certain poems. But for ourselves, we know that
these verses are brilliant, and those are rhymed bullshit. And so on
And this subjective assessment can be objectified by averaging it ove
all members of society. This makes it possible to assess whether the
definitions of a particular humanitarian theory are strict to the extent
that this is achievable in a given field, or whether it is sciencelike
empty talk. More about this and with examples -in the book.
The unambiguity of concepts and their unambiguous binding to the
set of objects of reality is a necessary condition, but not sufficient for
the unambiguity and reliability of the conclusions of the theory. But is it
possible to obtain unambiguous and reliable conclusions about
unambiguous concepts, and, if possible, how does science achieve
his? I say that this can and is achieved only with the help of the
axiomatic construction of the theory
First, let me remind you that the system of axioms is one of the
ways to unambiguously define concepts. This means that not only by
setting the system axioms, we thereby define its basic system of
concepts, but vice versa, the system of basic concepts of a theory
determines its system of axioms. And from here it follows that the
binding of concepts to the set of objects of reality means the binding
of axioms to the same reality. In other words, the axioms, which are a
special case of conclusions-statements of the theory, are true, true for
that area of reality, for that set of real objects, which is determined by
tolerances to the nominal definitions of concepts. Moreover, they are
true - with the accuracy and reliability that is determined by these
tolerances.
But, as is known, a system of axioms uniquely determines all
potential conclusions from it (theorem), regardless of the sequence in
which they are made. We can even swap axioms and separate
conclusions. In this case, the procedure for deriving conclusions will
change, but the set of statements of the theory (including axioms, as a
special case of conclusions) will remain unchanged. So, for example,
the fifth axiom of Euclid's geometry (about parallel lines) can be
interchanged with the theorem stating that the sum of the angles of a
triangle is 180 degrees and all other conclusions of the theory will
remain unchanged (only the procedure for deriving them will change).
Similarly, Newton's second law and the law of momentum- any of
them can be taken as a postulate, getting the other as a conclusion
while maintaining the rest of the theory building. </div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M11 4H4a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v14a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h14a2 2 0 0 0 2-2v-7"></path><path d="M18.5 2.5a2.121 2.121 0 0 1 3 3L12 15l-4 1 1-4 9.5-9.5z"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-[#444654]"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col relative item