 19.9254 10.8098 19.9058V10.6071C10.8107 9.18295 11.2173 7.78848 11.9819 6.58696C12.7466 5.38544 13.8377 4.42659 15.1275 3.82264C16.4173 3.21869 17.8524 2.99464 19.2649 3.1767C20.6775 3.35876 22.0089 3.93941 23.1034 4.85067C23.0427 4.88379 22.937 4.94215 22.8668 4.98473L14.9024 9.58517C14.7025 9.69878 14.5366 9.86356 14.4215 10.0626C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>In Voin's unified method of justification, a concept is defined unambiguously in what he terms the nominal definition. Here, the properties of real objects corresponding to the definition are listed, along with a quantitative measure of these properties. Following this, acceptable deviations from the nominal definition are specified, which uniquely determines the set of real objects that satisfy the definition. These permissible deviations are based on the required accuracy and reliability of the theory's predictions in relation to a specific problem.</p><p>However, in actual scientific practice, these nominal definitions and permissible deviations are not always explicitly stated. They are either implied, or the theory can be dismissed as non-scientific. For example, in geometric optics, light rays are considered straight and deviations from zero curvature are not specified because they are negligible under Earth conditions. However, if geometric optics were to be applied in space, where light rays bend due to gravitational forces of stars, these allowable deviations would need to be specified to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the predictions.</p><p>There's a challenge in applying the unified method to humanities where most concepts lack a quantitative measure for their attributes. This does not mean that precision is unattainable in humanities. While we can't quantify the talent in certain poems, we can differentiate between brilliant verses and poorly constructed ones. Subjective assessments can be objectified by averaging them over all members of society, which allows an evaluation of the strictness of the definitions of a particular humanitarian theory.</p><p>Voin underscores the importance of the axiomatic construction of theories for achieving unambiguous and reliable conclusions. In an axiomatic system, the system of basic concepts determines its system of axioms, and vice versa. Thus, the binding of concepts to the set of objects in reality also means the binding of axioms to that reality. The axioms, which are special cases of the theory's conclusions, are true for the area of reality determined by the tolerances to the nominal definitions of the concepts, within a certain level of accuracy and reliability.</p><p>The system of axioms uniquely determines all potential conclusions (theorems), regardless of the order in which they are made. Therefore, swapping axioms and theorems would only change the procedure for deriving conclusions, but the set of theory statements would remain unchanged. For example, the fifth axiom of Euclid's geometry (about parallel lines) can be interchanged with the theorem stating that the sum of the angles of a triangle is 180 degrees, and all other conclusions of the theory will remain unchanged.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="flex ml-auto gap-2 rounded-md p-1 hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2"></path><rect x="8" y="2" width="8" height="4" rx="1" ry="1"></rect></svg></button><div class="flex gap-1"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M14 9V5a3 3 0 0 0-3-3l-4 9v11h11.28a2 2 0 0 0 2-1.7l1.38-9a2 2 0 0 0-2-2.3zM7 22H4a2 2 0 0 1-2-2v-7a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h3"></path></svg></button><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M10 15v4a3 3 0 0 0 3 3l4-9V2H5.72a2 2 0 0 0-2 1.7l-1.38 9a2 2 0 0 0 2 2.3zm7-13h2.67A2.31 2.31 0 0 1 22 4v7a2.31 2.31 0 0 1-2.33 2H17"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 dark:bg-gray-800"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col relative items-end"><div class="w-[30px]"><div class="relative flex"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; max-width: 100%;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; max-width: 100%;"><img alt="" aria-hidden="true" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20version=%271.1%27%20width=%2738%27%20height=%2738%27/%3e" style="display: block; max-width: 100%; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;"></span><img alt="User" src="https://chat.openai.com/_next/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2Fa%2FAGNmyxbfUJGaUXxADgtF19b5ZhmrVKp8-tY9hQf2Jfmp%3Ds96-c&amp;w=96&amp;q=75" decoding="async" data-nimg="intrinsic" class="rounded-sm" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" width="30" height="30"></span></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Thus, in the axiomatic
construction of a theory, not only the axioms, but also all the
conclusions of the theory turn out to be true (with a given accuracy
and probability) for that area of reality, for that set of real objects,
which is determined by tolerances to the nominal definitions of the
basic concepts of the theory.
Well okay, the reader will say here, for example, the axiomatic
method of constructing a theory provides us with the reliability and
unambiguity of the conclusions of the theory (provided that the
definition of basic concepts and their binding to reality is
unambiguous). But can any theory be built or rebuilt axiomatically?
And is it only the axiomatic method of construction that ensures the
above requirements? After all, the vast majority of theories, even
physical, not to mention humanitarian, are not built strictly
axiomatically. What, all of them should be unconditionally thrown into
the trash, into pseudoscience? Indeed, in the same physics, along with
the axiomatic, the genetic, which is also a constructive, method of
constructing a theory, is used, described, for example, by V. Stiopin (B
C. CTennH. CTahObnehne Hayuho teopun Mh., 34-Bo bry,1976).
As for the fundamental possibility of axiomatization of an arbitrary
theory, there are many objections against it, some of which belong to
V. Stiopin. I refute these objections in my book mentioned above and
in the article "On the question of the fundamental possibility of
axiomatization of an arbitrary scientific theory" (Bulletin of the Perm
University. Philosophy. Psychology. Sociology. 2013. Issue 49 (16). P
101-109), to which I refer the reader.
As for the possibility of satisfying the requirements of reliability
and uniqueness of theory conclusions not with the help of the
axiomatic method of constructing a theory, then, yes, I argue that only
the axiomatic method can provide them. In particular, the genetic
method does not provide them. The difference between the genetic
and axiomatic methods is that the basic element of the axiomatic
method is the concept, while the basic element of the genetic method
is the "abstract object" described by V. Stiopin in his book mentioned
above. The concept captures only those properties of objects that are
determined by axioms. By the very essence of the axiomatic method, it
is forbidden to introduce into consideration the properties of the
objects under study that are not fixed in axioms and, therefore, in
concepts. While the essence of the genetic method is that we just
introduce in the "thought experiment" the properties of objects that are
not fixed in the initial definition of an abstract object. This is a very
valuable heuristic tool, valuable in the genesis phase. </div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M11 4H4a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v14a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h14a2 2 0 0 0 2-2v-7"></path><path d="M18.5 2.5a2.121 2.121 0 0 1 3 3L12 15l-4 1 1-4 9.5-9.5z"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-[#444654]"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col relative