.8122 19.9254 10.8098 19.9058V10.6071C10.8107 9.18295 11.2173 7.78848 11.9819 6.58696C12.7466 5.38544 13.8377 4.42659 15.1275 3.82264C16.4173 3.21869 17.8524 2.99464 19.2649 3.1767C20.6775 3.35876 22.0089 3.93941 23.1034 4.85067C23.0427 4.88379 22.937 4.94215 22.8668 4.98473L14.9024 9.58517C14.7025 9.69878 14.5366 9.86356 14.4215 10.0626C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>In the axiomatic construction of a theory, all conclusions (not just the axioms) are accurate and reliable for the specific area of reality or the set of real objects determined by the tolerances to the nominal definitions of the basic concepts of the theory.</p><p>There may be doubts about whether all theories can be constructed or reconstructed axiomatically, and whether the axiomatic method is the only one that can ensure the reliability and unambiguity of conclusions. Most theories, even physical ones, are not built strictly axiomatically. There are also genetic (or constructive) methods of constructing theories. However, Voin insists that it is only the axiomatic method that can satisfy the requirements of reliability and uniqueness of theory conclusions.</p><p>The key difference between the genetic and axiomatic methods is that the basic element of the axiomatic method is the concept, while the basic element of the genetic method is the "abstract object". The concept captures only those properties of objects that are determined by axioms, disallowing the consideration of properties not fixed in axioms. On the other hand, the genetic method allows the introduction of properties not fixed in the initial definition of an abstract object in a thought experiment. This is a valuable heuristic tool in the genesis phase.</p><p>In conclusion, the axiomatic method, according to Voin, is the ideal method for constructing theories to achieve unambiguity and reliability. However, other methods like the genetic method also have their place, particularly in the genesis phase of theory development, where they can serve as valuable heuristic tools.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="flex ml-auto gap-2 rounded-md p-1 hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2"></path><rect x="8" y="2" width="8" height="4" rx="1" ry="1"></rect></svg></button><div class="flex gap-1"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M14 9V5a3 3 0 0 0-3-3l-4 9v11h11.28a2 2 0 0 0 2-1.7l1.38-9a2 2 0 0 0-2-2.3zM7 22H4a2 2 0 0 1-2-2v-7a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h3"></path></svg></button><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M10 15v4a3 3 0 0 0 3 3l4-9V2H5.72a2 2 0 0 0-2 1.7l-1.38 9a2 2 0 0 0 2 2.3zm7-13h2.67A2.31 2.31 0 0 1 22 4v7a2.31 2.31 0 0 1-2.33 2H17"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 dark:bg-gray-800"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col relative items-end"><div class="w-[30px]"><div class="relative flex"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; max-width: 100%;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; max-width: 100%;"><img alt="" aria-hidden="true" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20version=%271.1%27%20width=%2738%27%20height=%2738%27/%3e" style="display: block; max-width: 100%; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;"></span><img alt="User" src="https://chat.openai.com/_next/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2Fa%2FAGNmyxbfUJGaUXxADgtF19b5ZhmrVKp8-tY9hQf2Jfmp%3Ds96-c&amp;w=96&amp;q=75" decoding="async" data-nimg="intrinsic" class="rounded-sm" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" width="30" height="30"></span></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">But it destroys
the uniqueness of theory conclusions and violates the uniqueness of
what we are talking about, and therefore must be eliminated in the
justification phase. In today's scientific practice, the phases of genesis
and substantiation are by no means always separated. Therefore, in
practice, even in physics, we often see a mixture, alternation of a
genetic construction with, if not a purely axiomatic, then a deductive
development of the theory. Such a combination, of course, means the
incompleteness of the justification of the theory according to the
unified method of justification. But it does not necessarily mean that
such a theory cannot be axiomatically completed or rebuilt, i.e. does
not mean that this theory is necessarily unscientific, pseudoscientific
In my book, I give an example of how Hilbert completed the axiomatic
geometry of Euclid, who, although he was the father of the axiomatic
method, still did not completely build his geometry purely axiomatically
and interleaved in his "Principles of Geometry" an axiomatic
development with a constructive method, in particular with the so-
called thought experiment
Thus, we are not talking that the recognition of the unified method of
justification will lead to the inclusion of almost all modern science in
pseudoscience, especially in the field of natural sciences. But its
application will help even in the field of natural sciences to detect
paradoxes and contradictions and either eliminate them, or recognize
the corresponding theory as not scientific and the need to create a new
theory. Especially in the humanitarian sphere.
Another category of questions that I had to face in various
discussions on the unified method of justification were questions like
how to deal with such criteria as heuristics, the beauty of a theory, etc.,
which are often used, say, in modern physics to select promising areas
of research? These criteria do not seem to intersect in any way, neither
with an axiomatic construction, nor with the unified method of
justification in general. So, is it necessary to abandon these criteria in
science altogether?
The answer is this. Yes, these criteria do not intersect with the
unified method of justification, but this does not mean that they have
no place in science. The only question is where is this place. Their
place is in the phase of the genesis of the theory. Choosing between
competing hypotheses on the subject of which one to focus the efforts
of the scientific team on and which one to finance from a limited
resource, we can take into account both the beauty and heuristic of the
theory (hypothesis) and much more. But the beauty and heuristic
nature of the theory-hypothesis by no means guarantee us the
uniqueness of its inputs and their truth-reliability. Greek myths are very
beautiful and, in a sense, very heuristic, because they allow you to
explain anything with explanations like "The sea is worried because
Neptune is angry." But what this has to do with science and truth, we know.
