.2173 7.78848 11.9819 6.58696C12.7466 5.38544 13.8377 4.42659 15.1275 3.82264C16.4173 3.21869 17.8524 2.99464 19.2649 3.1767C20.6775 3.35876 22.0089 3.93941 23.1034 4.85067C23.0427 4.88379 22.937 4.94215 22.8668 4.98473L14.9024 9.58517C14.7025 9.69878 14.5366 9.86356 14.4215 10.0626C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>Voin argues that although the genetic method serves as a valuable tool in the genesis phase of theory development, it can disrupt the uniqueness of theory conclusions and breach the uniqueness of the subject under discussion. Therefore, it should be eliminated in the justification phase. In current scientific practice, the genesis and substantiation phases are not always clearly distinguished, leading to a mix of genetic and axiomatic (or deductive) theory construction. This mix signifies the theory's incomplete justification according to the unified method. However, this does not necessarily imply that such a theory is pseudoscientific; it may still be completed or reconstructed axiomatically.</p><p>Voin references Hilbert's completion of Euclid's axiomatic geometry as an example of how a theory can be properly axiomatized. Despite being the father of the axiomatic method, Euclid did not purely build his geometry in this way and incorporated elements of constructive method into his "Principles of Geometry".</p><p>Adopting the unified method of justification will not necessarily categorize most modern science as pseudoscientific, particularly in the field of natural sciences. However, its application could help detect paradoxes and contradictions, facilitating their elimination or the acknowledgement of the theory as non-scientific, thus indicating the need for a new theory. This is particularly true in the humanities.</p><p>Voin also addresses questions regarding criteria such as heuristics and beauty, which are often used in modern physics to select promising areas of research. Although these criteria do not directly intersect with the unified method of justification, they still have a place in science, specifically in the genesis phase of theory development. In selecting hypotheses to pursue, criteria such as beauty and heuristics can be considered, but they do not guarantee the uniqueness of the inputs or their truth-reliability.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="flex ml-auto gap-2 rounded-md p-1 hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2"></path><rect x="8" y="2" width="8" height="4" rx="1" ry="1"></rect></svg></button><div class="flex gap-1"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M14 9V5a3 3 0 0 0-3-3l-4 9v11h11.28a2 2 0 0 0 2-1.7l1.38-9a2 2 0 0 0-2-2.3zM7 22H4a2 2 0 0 1-2-2v-7a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h3"></path></svg></button><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M10 15v4a3 3 0 0 0 3 3l4-9V2H5.72a2 2 0 0 0-2 1.7l-1.38 9a2 2 0 0 0 2 2.3zm7-13h2.67A2.31 2.31 0 0 1 22 4v7a2.31 2.31 0 0 1-2.33 2H17"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 dark:bg-gray-800"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col relative items-end"><div class="w-[30px]"><div class="relative flex"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; max-width: 100%;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; max-width: 100%;"><img alt="" aria-hidden="true" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20version=%271.1%27%20width=%2738%27%20height=%2738%27/%3e" style="display: block; max-width: 100%; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;"></span><img alt="User" src="https://chat.openai.com/_next/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2Fa%2FAGNmyxbfUJGaUXxADgtF19b5ZhmrVKp8-tY9hQf2Jfmp%3Ds96-c&amp;w=96&amp;q=75" decoding="async" data-nimg="intrinsic" class="rounded-sm" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" width="30" height="30"></span></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words">Another question-objection against a unified method of
substantiation and, in particular, the axiomatic construction of a theory
is as follows. As is known, a finite set of facts, experimental data can
be covered by the conclusions of more than one system of axioms or
a system of corresponding concepts. The question is, which one is
true, which one to choose, and what is the relationship between
theories based on such systems of axioms?
I'Il start with relationships. An excellent illustration of this
relationship is provided by classical (Newtonian) mechanics and
Einstein's theory of relativity. In the region of speeds far from the speed
of light, both of these theories are true in the sense of truth that
science can only give. Namely, in this area of reality, they give
predictions that practically coincide and correspond to reality with
almost the same accuracy and probability. But outside this area, i.e
for speeds close to the speed of light, the theory of relativity continues
to give accurate and reliable predictions, and classical mechanics no
longer guarantees us either the accuracy or the reliability of its
predictions. (Because its concepts are tied to experience only for
speeds far from the speed of light). The general conclusion is this. All
theories built axiomatically with binding of axioms (concepts) to
experience in some area of reality are true (in the above sense) in this
area. But we will be able to judge the truth of each of them outside this
area only after the appearance of experimental data outside these
limits. But even after new experimental data appear and it turns out
that a particular axiomatically built theory does not work in the entire
extended area, this does not mean that it stops working and cannot be
used in the former reduced area. (What we do in the case of classical
mechanics). Thus, the real problem associated with the multiplicity of
possible systems of axioms that cover a specific set of facts with their
conclusions is not a choice between these systems, but that we do not
know in advance the limits of reliable application of any of them. And
therefore, the appearance of such "surprises" as the results of the
Michelson-Morley experiments cause an excessive storm of emotions
in the scientific community. This storm of emotions is connected
precisely with the lack of recognition of the unfied method of
substantiation and the resulting misunderstanding of the minimum
limits of the theory's reliability. Which, as follows from the above, are
determined by binding to the experience of basic concepts or axioms
It is important to note another circumstance in this context. If two
theories with different systems of axioms and different basic concepts
cover with their conclusions a certain set of facts of reality, then the
full areas of applicability of each of them never completely coincide
They can have applications that include one another, as is the case
with relativity and classical mechanics. (The field of relativity theory
includes the field of classical mechanics as a part). But they can also
have intersecting areas, where, in addition to the common part, each has its own.

Finally, in this context, another question arises about the
relationship between close or similar concepts of such theories. Let's
say absolute Newtonian and relative Einsteinian time. Or
representations of the electron in various physical theories, first as a
charged ball without mass, then the same, but with mass, then as an
electron cloud smeared along the orbit of its rotation around the
nucleus of an atom, and, finally, as a packet of electromagnetic waves
Or, in a broader formulation, this is a question about the ontological
essence of physical and scientific concepts in general. Without going
into details (for which I refer the reader to the book), I will only say that
close concepts of successive fundamental theories are successive
approximations of the absolute ontological essence in the process of
infinite approximation of our knowledge to it through successive fundamental theories.

