s obstacles, including resistance to new thinking, and feels that a strategy for overcoming these obstacles has not been adequately developed. He argues that there is an overestimation of determinism in human development and an underestimation of the possibility of dramatic developments, including self-destruction.</p><p>Voin highlights a key obstacle: the absence of a common language, not referring to spoken languages, but a system of universally understood concepts and methods of substantiating statements. This lack of a common language hinders agreement on the correct course of development for humanity and the resolution of universal human problems.</p><p>He illustrates this with international negotiations on armed conflicts, where each side asserts its own interpretation of peace, justice, and human interests. This can lead to misunderstanding and conflict, as seen with religious scriptures, where different interpretations can lead to violence and extremism.</p><p>The author concludes that to develop a universal ideology and value system, a common language is needed, which essentially means a universally accepted and reliable method of substantiating the truth. Without this, attempts to reach agreement may fail or result in unjust or harmful outcomes.</p><p>The author critiques the geoversal project's proposal to base a universal human value system on values common in each civilization, arguing that this is insufficient for developing a universal ideology and value system that will ensure safe, sustainable, and acceptable development of humanity. He points out that we live in a unique era of globalization and rapid scientific and technological progress, which has changed the conditions of our existence and presented new problems. Therefore, values from previous civilizations may not be applicable in our era.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><but