ified method of substantiating scientific theories is not explicitly presented but exists as a stereotype of scientific thinking. Consequently, natural scientists can somewhat communicate using this common language, but representatives of humanities and social sciences, who are generally unfamiliar with this method, cannot.</p><p>Voin's philosophy suggests that even when concepts and conclusions change between theories, if both theories are based on a unified method of substantiation, the concepts are tied to experience. He believes that a unified method of substantiation can provide a common language for scientists, including those in the humanities, politicians, and ordinary people, assuming it's introduced into the education system.</p><p>In his work, Voin presents theories on morality, determinism and freedom, and the spirit, all based on his unified method of substantiation. He proposes a new interpretation of the teachings of the Bible, a new macroeconomic theory, and discusses the consequences of not applying his method, especially in the humanities and social sciences.</p><p>He concludes by stressing the importance of including his unified method of substantiation of scientific theories in the project of a geoversal civilization. He believes that this method is compatible with the principles underlying the geoversal project, such as the Oneness of All Matters, The Oneness of All Humanities, The Oneness of All Faiths, and so on.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shr